description:
#GW11 Match-up: Team xG vs. Opponent xGC 

Data: @fbref
- GW1 '23/24 - GW10 '24/25 
- Home/Away are considered, except for the Promoted teams, for which '24/25 season data are averaged 

‚≠ïÔ∏è TOT have the second-highest xG per game (1.98)  this season, just behind MCI (1.99), while IPS have conceded the highest xG in the league. This couldn‚Äôt be any better matchup for TOT.

‚≠ïÔ∏èWith a home advantage, LIV‚Äôs fixture against AVL seems more favorable compared to MCI playing BHA away. However, note that AVL‚Äôs defense has been significantly stronger than BHA‚Äôs this season, making the Salah vs. Haaland captaincy choice a close 50/50 call.

‚≠ïÔ∏èARS remain a solid attacking side, though they rank slightly lower and fall in the fourth quadrant due to higher xGs of teams like LIV, CHE, TOT, and MCI. ARS‚Äôs xG tends to dip in away games as they focus more on defense, which may make CHE vs. ARS a low scoring game, though it will largely depend on game states.

‚≠ïÔ∏èWhile BRE boast excellent attacking data positioning them in the first quadrant, BOU have shown improvement both offensively and defensively.

‚≠ïÔ∏èMUN had a goal fest against LEI‚Äôs second team in the EFL Cup last week. It wouldn‚Äôt be surprising if they score big again at Old Trafford if they can capitalize on their chances.

‚≠ïÔ∏èWOL also have a favorable matchup against SOU.

‚≠ïÔ∏èFUL are in Q4 primarily due to their poor underlying data in away games and CRY's strong defensive stats at home last season. However, it‚Äôs worth noting that FUL have been performing phenomenally, while CRY have been struggling this season.

name: San‚ñà‚ñà‚ñàRud‚ñà‚ñà‚ñàajh‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà
description:
Reporting at Crewe vs Notts County today for @5liveSport.

I hope @ryancooney_6 & Jacob Bedeau manage a moment together.

On opposite sides of the pitch, after being teammates at Morecambe.

But more than that, two of the brightest recent prospects from #BuryFC before the expulsion. 

Both thrown into the deep end, moving on to PL/ch clubs before building their experience back in the EFL. 

Ryan came to Bury at 9. Captained every age group from u11s-18 and was given the armband by Ryan Lowe in our final league game, when the end was nearing. He left Bury for then PL Burnley. 

Jacob was starting as a centre half at SIXTEEN in League One, joining our academy after leaving Leyton Orient - and earning a move to Villa as a result. He lived with my best friend‚Äôs mum @NotjuliKaye in digs and by all accounts was much better behaved than their actual son.

description:
I DIDN'T CHOOSE ASTON VILLA....IT CHOSE ME...
Featuring Nicklas Jansson

My Name is Nicklas, and I am a Villa fanü¶Å
I live in G√§vleborg, Swedenüá∏üá™ International fan.

@AVFCOfficial #VillaChoseMe #UTV #avfcü¶Å

STORY1‚É£2‚É£8‚É£

Here is my Villa story....
My first memory of watching British football dates back to around 1995-97, when I was about 5-7 years old. My grandmother loved any kind of sport, and I picked up that habit from her. In Sweden, we have a tradition of watching English football on Saturdays, primarily because our football season runs from April to November. Even though I watched various sports, there was something special about English football. I remember tuning in every Saturday, but I didn‚Äôt support any particular team.

A few years later, I read about Aston Villa in a newspaper, and something clicked‚ÄîI decided that was the team I would support. I followed Villa through teletext, and a few years later, I could watch most games on cable TV. I distinctly remember Juan Pablo Angel‚Äôs goal against Bolton in the League Cup; that moment made him my favorite player. It was an underrated goal, in my opinion.

I didn‚Äôt attend any games growing up since my family was more into ice hockey. However, when I was 20, I moved to Brighton for six months to study. I realized this was a perfect opportunity to visit Villa Park for the first time. I emailed Sussex Lions (shoutout to everyone involved at the time), and they promptly helped me arrange everything. My first game was against Manchester City, and it turned out to be the perfect match. Villa played like heroes, and our new signing, Darren Bent, scored. The first few minutes felt surreal‚Äîhaving watched the games on TV for so long, being there in person was an incredible experience.

That spring, I ended up attending every game at Villa Park and even made my first away trip to Upton Park, which became my favorite Villa moment when Gabby scored a late winner. I only saw Villa lose once that season.

When I returned to Sweden, I decided I needed to go back at least once a year, which I did to catch a game or two. My first daughter was born in 2019 and my second in 2022, and unfortunately, I haven‚Äôt traveled to England since then. However, they are both Villa fans with their own shirts. I‚Äôve gone back to watching every game on television, but I hope to be back at Villa Park very soon.

Sometimes it feels surreal to see the progress the club has made in recent years. It can be frustrating, too, considering how expensive it has become to watch Villa, and I feel for the fans who supported the team during our relegation. But now we‚Äôre playing Champions League football, and I plan to enjoy every second of it!

Thats my Villa Story!üíúüíô

Kind regards
Nicklas
